<!-- end video:1636 --><p></p><p>Theoretically, this means that usability i=
ncludes accessibility, since a product that is inaccessible is also unusabl=
e to someone with a disability; <em>practically</em>, however, usability <e=
m>tends not </em>to specifically focus on the <a href=3D"https://www.intera=
ction-design.org/literature/topics/ux-design" title=3D"What is User Experie=
nce Design?">user experience</a> of people with disabilities.<strong> Acces=
sibility, on the other hand, is concerned with whether </strong><em><strong=
>all</strong></em><strong> users are able to access an equivalent user expe=
rience, however they encounter a product or service </strong>(e.g., using <=
a href=3D"https://www.interaction-design.org/literature/topics/assistive-te=
chnology" title=3D"What is Assistive Technology?">assistive devices</a>). U=
nlike usability, accessibility focuses on people with disabilities.</p><fig=
ure><img data-src=3D"https://public-images.interaction-design.org/tags/td_a=
ccessibility_02.png" alt=3D"" loading=3D"lazy" width=3D"1001" height=3D"772=
"><figcaption><p><small class=3D"copyright">=C2=A9 Interaction Design Found=
ation, CC BY-SA 4.0</small></p></figcaption></figure><h2 id=3D"accessible_d=
esigns_help_everyone-3">Accessible Designs Help Everyone</h2><p>Accessibili=
ty is not only the <strong>right thing to do</strong>, but often also <stro=
ng>brings benefits to </strong><em><strong>all</strong></em><strong> users<=
/strong>. That=E2=80=99s because accessibility features that help people wi=
th disabilities often help other people, too. For instance, video captions =
that help people with hearing difficulties also help a person who is watchi=
ng the video on mute (e.g., in a social media feed). Legible, high-contrast=
 text that helps people with vision difficulties also helps people with per=
fect eyesight who are using the app outdoors in bright sunlight. <strong>Ma=
ny users=E2=80=94</strong><em><strong>whatever</strong></em><strong> their =
abilities=E2=80=94will face challenges due to demanding contexts</strong>. =
When you design for <em>all </em>ability levels, you can create products an=
d services anyone can use and enjoy=E2=80=94or at least find helpful or cal=
ming.</p><p>Although accessibility is a critical factor that impacts design=
, many brands overlook it. Based on a 2011 World Health Organization report=
 concerning disability, however, you=E2=80=99ll exclude about 15% of Earth=
=E2=80=99s population if you don=E2=80=99t make your design accessible. Fur=
thermore, many jurisdictions=E2=80=94including the E.U.=E2=80=94have penalt=
ies for failure to create accessible designs. However,<strong> designing fo=
r accessibility makes sense on more than a legal level; it brings </strong>=
<em><strong>benefits</strong></em>, including these:</p><ul><li><p><strong>=
Improved SEO from semantic HTML</strong></p></li><li><p><strong>Opportuniti=
es to reach more users on more devices, in more settings/environments</stro=
ng></p></li><li><p><strong>Enhanced public image for your brand</strong></p=
></li></ul><h2 id=3D"types_of_accessibility_issues-4">Types of Accessibilit=
y Issues</h2><p>You should <strong>consider the </strong><em><strong>number=
</strong></em><strong> and </strong><em><strong>types</strong></em><strong>=
 of potential accessibility issues users will have</strong>. These are comm=
on barriers:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Visual</strong> (e.g., <a href=3D"https:=
//www.interaction-design.org/literature/topics/color" title=3D"What is Colo=
r in UX Design?">color</a> blindness)</p></li><li><p><strong>Motor/mobility=
</strong> (e.g., wheelchair-user concerns)</p></li><li><p><strong>Auditory<=
/strong> (hearing difficulties)</p></li><li><p><strong>Seizures</strong> (e=
specially photosensitive epilepsy)</p></li><li><p><strong>Learning/cognitiv=
e</strong> (e.g., dyslexia)</p></li></ul><p>Ability barriers can also <em>a=
rise</em> for <em>any</em> user:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Incidental</strong> =
(e.g., sleep-deprivation)</p></li><li><p><strong>Environmental</strong> (e.=
g., using a mobile device underground)</p></li></ul><figure><img data-src=
=3D"https://public-images.interaction-design.org/tags/td_accessibility_3.pn=
g" alt=3D"" loading=3D"lazy" width=3D"1001" height=3D"512"><figcaption><p><=
small class=3D"copyright">=C2=A9 Interaction Design Foundation, CC BY-SA 4.=
0</small></p></figcaption></figure><p>The possibilities are virtually limit=
less regarding who might be trying to access your product/service.</p><bloc=
kquote><p><em>=E2=80=9CWhen UX doesn=E2=80=99t consider ALL users, shouldn=
=E2=80=99t it be known as =E2=80=9CSOME User Experience=E2=80=9D or=E2=80=
=A6 SUX?=E2=80=9D <br><br>=E2=80=94 Billy Gregory, Senior Accessibility Eng=
ineer<br></em></p></blockquote><p></p><figure><img data-src=3D"https://publ=
ic-images.interaction-design.org/tags/td_accessibility_05.png" alt=3D"" loa=
ding=3D"lazy" width=3D"1001" height=3D"422"><figcaption><p><small class=3D"=
copyright">=C2=A9 Interaction Design Foundation, CC BY-SA 4.0</small></p></=
figcaption></figure><h2 id=3D"practical_guidelines_for_accessibility-5">Pra=
ctical Guidelines for Accessibility</h2><p>The World Wide Web Consortium (W=
3C) stipulates standards for accessible design in its latest <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.interaction-design.org/literature/topics/web-content-accessibility=
-guidelines" title=3D"What are The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WC=
AG)?">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines</a> (WCAG). You can follow these=
 essential points to accommodate users with diverse abilities:</p><ul><li><=
